'''John E. Bryson''' (born July 24, 1943)<ref>[http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/biography/A-E/Bryson-John-E-1943.html John E. Bryson 1943-], ''Reference for Business', Encyclopedia of Business 2nd edition</ref> is the former [[United States Secretary of Commerce]], the 37th person to hold the post since its establishment in 1913. Prior to this, he served as the Chairman, Chief Executive Officer and President of [[Edison International]], the parent company of [[Southern California Edison]] and as director of [[The Boeing Company]].

The Senate confirmed Bryson as Secretary of Commerce by a 74–26 vote on October 20, 2011.<ref name="roll call"/> He was sworn in on October 21, 2011. Bryson took a leave of absence in June 2012 for medical tests due to [[seizure]]s that were related to a [[hit and run (vehicular)|hit and run]]. On June 21, 2012 Bryson resigned because, "the work that [Commerce employees] do to help America’s entrepreneurs and businesses build our economy and create jobs is more important now than ever and I have come to the conclusion that I need to step down to prevent distractions from this critical mission."<ref>{{cite news|title=Letter from Secretary Bryson to Commerce Employees |url=https://www.commerce.gov/blog/2012/06/21/letter-secretary-bryson-commerce-employees |accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>

== Early life and education ==
Bryson was born in New York City. His father operated a [[sawmill]].<ref name=lat/> He graduated from [[Cleveland High School (Portland, Oregon)|Cleveland High School]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], in 1961.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pope|first=Charles|title=John Bryson brings Portland roots as nominee to lead Commerce Department |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2011/05/john_bryson_brings_portland_ro.html|accessdate=31 May 2011|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=May 31, 2011}}</ref> He received his bachelor's degree from [[Stanford University]] in 1965 and his [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree from [[Yale Law School]] in 1969.

== Career ==
In 1970, with other recent Yale Law graduates, Bryson helped found and served as legal counsel for the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]].<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-01/news/mn-1223_1_natural-resources-defense-council Ex-Environment Activist Will Take Helm at Edison], Larry B. Stammer, Michael Parrish, Times staff writers, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', October 1, 1990</ref><ref>[http://www.anderson.ucla.edu/x14873.xml Edison International Chairman John E. Bryson to Deliver UCLA Anderson Commencement Address, June 16], [[UCLA Anderson]], May 16, 2006</ref> From 1976 to 1979, Bryson served as chairman of the [[California State Water Resources Control Board]], and from 1979 to 1982, he served as president of the [[California Public Utilities Commission]]. In 1983 Bryson worked for the law firm of [[Morrison and Foerster]] in the San Francisco office. Bryson joined [[Edison International]] in 1984,<ref>{{cite news| title=John Bryson: Green At Heart, Greener In The Wallet | url=https://www.forbes.com/2001/05/03/bryson.html | work=Forbes | first=Betsy | last=Schiffman}}</ref> and served as director from 1990 until his retirement on July 31, 2008.<ref>[http://www.edison.com/ourcompany/management.asp?id=1836 John E. Bryson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060314001842/http://www.edison.com/ourcompany/management.asp?id=1836 |date=2006-03-14 }}, [[Edison (company)|Edison International]]</ref>

Bryson was a director of [[The Boeing Company]], [[W. M. Keck Foundation]], and [[The Walt Disney Company]], and a former Director/Trustee for three [[Western Asset Management]] funds at [[Legg Mason]]. He serves or has served on a number of educational, environmental and other nonprofit boards, including chairman of the [[California Business Roundtable]], a trustee of [[Stanford University]], a trustee of [[California Institute of Technology]], co-chairman of the [[Pacific Council on International Policy]], and chairman of the [[Public Policy Institute of California]].<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/businessweek/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=301893&ticker=KKR:US&previousCapId=410467&previousTitle=DEUTSCHE%20BANK%20AG-REGISTERED John E. Bryson], ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.ppic.org/main/bio.asp?i=411 John E. Bryson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814044816/http://www.ppic.org/main/bio.asp?i=411 |date=2011-08-14 }}, [[Public Policy Institute of California]]</ref>

== Secretary of Commerce ==
[[File:Barack Obama with John Bryson and Ron Kirk.jpg|right|thumb|Then-Secretary Bryson, along with President [[Barack Obama]] and U.S. Trade Representative [[Ron Kirk]] at a press conference in the rose garden of the White House in March 2012.]]
On May 31, 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] nominated Bryson to succeed [[Gary Locke]] as the [[United States Secretary of Commerce]].<ref>[http://whitehouse.blogs.cnn.com/2011/05/31/obama-makes-it-official/ Obama makes it official], Alexander Mooney, [[CNN]]'', May 31, 2011</ref> Citing Bryson's environmental views, [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] [[James Inhofe]], a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] from [[Oklahoma]], put a [[Senate hold|hold]] on his nomination in July.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/12/us-usa-commerce-nominee-idUSTRE76B7CE20110712 Senator vows to block Commerce nominee Bryson]</ref> The Senate later reached a unanimous consent agreement to vote on Bryson's nomination, and the Senate confirmed Bryson by a 74–26 vote on October 20, 2011.<ref name="roll call">All 51 Democratic Senators and both independents voted for confirmation, but the Republican caucus split 21-26 against. See [[Confirmations of Barack Obama's Cabinet#Confirmation roll call votes|Obama confirmations, 2010]], [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=112&session=1&vote=00176 U.S. Senate roll call no. 176 (112th Cong. 1st session)] or [http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/112/senate/1/votes/176/ ''Washington Post'' votes database (112th Congress, 1st session, vote 176)]</ref> He was sworn in on October 21, 2011, becoming the 37th Secretary of the [[Department of Commerce]].<ref>[https://www.commerce.gov/news/press-releases/2011/10/21/john-bryson-sworn-37th-secretary-commerce Press Release, John Bryson Sworn In as 37th Secretary of Commerce ]</ref>

As Secretary of Commerce, Bryson co-chaired the White House Office of Manufacturing Policy with [[Gene Sperling]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/print-edition/2011/12/16/bryson-co-chair-manufacturing-policy.html | title=John Bryson will co-chair White House's manufacturing policy office}}</ref>

=== 2012 traffic accidents and resignation ===
On June 9, 2012, Bryson was involved in a pair of car crashes in [[San Gabriel, California]] and [[Rosemead, California]], which were investigated as possible [[hit and run (vehicular)|felony hit and run]]. He is said to have been found unconscious at the site of the second crash.  A Department of Commerce spokesperson confirmed he was involved in a crash, and said Bryson had suffered from a seizure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sheriff.lacounty.gov/wps/portal/lasd/!ut/p/c5/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gLAwgwcjfzdDPw9Hf3dAswNjcyCDLRDwfpwK3CyRwib4ADOBro-3nk56bqF2Rnpzk6KioCAMV4niQ!/dl3/d3/L2dJQSEvUUt3QS9ZQnZ3LzZfOTAwMEdPQlMyRzZNOTBJQ1Q2S1Y0UDFPMzA!/?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=/wps/wcm/connect/lasd+content/lasd+site/home/home+top+stories/hit+and+run+traffic+collision+investigation+involving+u.s.+secretary+of+commerce |title=Hit and Run Traffic Collision Investigation Involving U.S. Secretary of Commerce |publisher=[[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]]/San Gabriel Police Department |date=June 10, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612104224/http://sheriff.lacounty.gov/wps/portal/lasd/%21ut/p/c5/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gLAwgwcjfzdDPw9Hf3dAswNjcyCDLRDwfpwK3CyRwib4ADOBro-3nk56bqF2Rnpzk6KioCAMV4niQ%21/dl3/d3/L2dJQSEvUUt3QS9ZQnZ3LzZfOTAwMEdPQlMyRzZNOTBJQ1Q2S1Y0UDFPMzA%21/?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2Fwps%2Fwcm%2Fconnect%2Flasd+content%2Flasd+site%2Fhome%2Fhome+top+stories%2Fhit+and+run+traffic+collision+investigation+involving+u.s.+secretary+of+commerce |archivedate=June 12, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/ci_20826734/breaking-u-s-secretary-commerce-john-bryson-suspected |title=Breaking: U.S. Secretary of Commerce John Bryson suspected of felony hit-and-run following San Gabriel Valley crashes |newspaper=[[Pasadena Star-News]] |author=Brian Day |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Ku1YJ59?url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/ci_20826734/breaking-u-s-secretary-commerce-john-bryson-suspected |date=June 10, 2012 |archivedate=June 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/06/us-commerce-secretary-accused-in-hit-and-run-crashes-found-unconcious.html|title=Commerce Secretary John Bryson accused in hit-and-run crashes|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=June 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/11/us-usa-bryson-crash-idUSBRE85A0K220120611|title=U.S. Commerce secretary investigated for hit-and-run car crash|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=June 11, 2012|first=Susan|last=Heavey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/06/commerce-secretary-john-bryson-suffered-seizure-during-crashes-spokeswoman-says.html | title=Commerce agency: Secretary John Bryson had seizure linked to crashes | work=The Los Angeles Times | date=June 11, 2012 | accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>  Los Angeles County prosecutors announced on July 3, 2012, that no criminal charges would be pursued.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jul/04/local/la-me-bryson-20120704 | work=Los Angeles Times | first1=Robert | last1=Faturechi | first2=Andrew | last2=Blankstein | title=John Bryson, former Commerce secretary, won't be charged in hit-runs | date=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

On June 11, Bryson announced in a memo that he was taking a medical leave of absence.  Deputy Secretary of Commerce [[Rebecca Blank]] began serving as Acting Secretary of Commerce.<ref>{{cite news|title=White House: Bryson to take medical leave|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/story/2012-06-11/john-bryson-leave/55537612/1|accessdate=11 June 2012 | work=USA Today|date=June 11, 2012}}</ref>

On June 21, 2012, Bryson announced his resignation from the post of Secretary of Commerce.<ref>{{cite news|title=John Bryson resigns as commerce secretary, citing recent seizure|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2012/06/21/gJQAkkissV_story.html|accessdate=June 21, 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 21, 2012|first1=Ed|last1=O'Keefe}}</ref>

==Later life==
Bryson joined the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] as a Distinguished Senior Public Policy Scholar in October 2012.<ref>Wilson Center (2012). [http://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/secretary-john-bryson-joins-wilson-center Secretary John Bryson Joins Wilson Center]. Retrieved 7 October 2012.</ref>

==Personal==
Bryson is married to Louise.<ref name=lat2>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/06/commerce-secretary-john-bryson-given-medication-for-seizure-after-crashes.html | work=Los Angeles Times | title=L.A. Now | date=June 11, 2012}}</ref> Their four daughters graduated from the [[Polytechnic School]] in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref name=lat>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-commerce-crash-20120612,0,6308707.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first1=Scott | last1=Gold | first2=Kate | last2=Mather | first3=Andrew | last3=Blankstein | title=Commerce Secretary Bryson faces tests after hit-and-runs | date=June 11, 2012}}</ref> Bryson and his wife both served on the school's Board of Trustees.<ref name=lat2/> Bryson and his wife reside in [[San Marino, California]].<ref>http://blockshopper.com/ca/los-angeles-county/san-marino/property/5328021020/1370-woodstock-road</ref>

